ation acts as the electrophile and attacks the electron-rich indole at C3 (the most reactive position).\n\nBut wait - the nitrogen going from NH to NH+ suggests something more complex. In a normal Friedel-Crafts on indole, the product would have the substituent at C3 and the NH would remain as NH. The fact that NH becomes NH+ suggests this might be better classified as a nucleophilic addition to the carbocation, where the indole acts as the nucleophile.\n\nActually, re-reading the SMIRKS more carefully:\n\nReactant indole part: [NH:12][CH:11]=[CH:10]\nProduct: [NH+:12]=[CH:11][CH:10]...[CH:20]\n\nSo in the product:\n- N:12 is now NH+ with a double bond to C:11\n- C:10 is now bonded to CH:20 (the former carbocation carbon)\n- C:11=C:10 double bond became C:11-C:10 single bond (with C:10 now sp3)\n\nThis is electrophilic aromatic substitution (Friedel-Crafts alkylation) on the indole. The carbocation attacks C3 of indole. The positive charge on nitrogen in the product is the arenium ion (Wheland intermediate) that would normally lose a proton to rearomatize, but in this mapped reaction, it's shown as the protonated intermediate.\n\nActually, looking at this again - the product shows NH+ with a double bond to C:11, and C:10 is sp3 bonded to CH:20. This is exactly the Wheland intermediate (sigma complex) of electrophilic aromatic substitution. The indole C3 attacks the carbocation, forming the sigma complex.\n\nBut since the product IS the Wheland intermediate (with NH+), this is still classified as electrophilic aromatic substitution (Friedel-Crafts alkylation).\n\nMechanistic class: electrophilic_aromatic_substitution (or Friedel-Crafts alkylation)\n\nReaction center: The bond formed between C:10 and C:20, and the charge transfer from C:20 to N:12 through the conjugated system.\n\nLet me be more precise about the reaction center:\n- Bond formed: C:10-C:20\n- Bond order change: C:11=C:10 → C:11-C:10 (double to single)\n- Bond order change: N:12-H to N:12= (NH to NH+, loss of aromaticity)\n- Charge: C+:20 → C:20 (neutral), N:12 → N+:12\n\nThe mechanistic class is electrophilic aromatic substitution (Friedel-Crafts alkylation).\n\nFor the answer format, since it asks for mechanistic class and the expected output schema is \"mechanistic_label\", I should provide the mechanistic class label.\n\nThe most appropriate label would be: electrophilic_aromatic_substitution\n\nOr more specifically: Friedel-Crafts_alkylation\n\nGiven the task asks for mechanistic class, I'll go with the broader but more standard classification."
